53 patients were enrolled in the study, including 26 caries-active (CA) and 27 caries-free (CF) adults. Patients were considered CA if they had 3 active caries lesions (ICDAS score 1-3), and CF if they had either ICDAS score 0 or ICDAS score of 1-3 where the lesion is inactive. At the start of the study subjects were instructed how to brush their teeth twice a day and had a washout period of one week using a dentifrice containing 1450 ppm fluoride as sodium monofluorophosphate (MFP) and an insoluble calcium compound. After 1 week, supragingival dental plaque was collected from either three active caries lesions sites in CA patients or 3 caries free sites in caries free patients by a sterile spoon excavator. Samples from the same participant were pooled in a tube containing RNAprotect (Qiagen, Hilden, Germany), thoroughly resuspended and placed into dry ice to flash freeze, which was named Baseline. At this point, patients continued to use the same 1,450 ppm MFP dentifrice with an insoluble calcium compound used during the washout period. After 3 months, another sample from the same sites was taken and processed by the same procedure (we refer to these samples as Fluoride). Patients received then a dentifrice with 1.5% arginine, 1450 ppm fluoride as a sodium MFP and an insoluble calcium compound, which they used for an additional 6 months. After 6 months, a third set of samples was collected and termed Fl-Arg. Sampling at all time points was repeated a week after the initial visit to have a replicate of samples collected. Replicates were combined to obtain enough nucleic acids concentration to perform the metagenome and metatranscriptome analyses. The same CA or CF teeth were sampled at every collection time point. Patients were asked to visit the clinic at least 12 hours after their last teeth brushing, meal or drink (anything but water).

A 4 L seawater sample was collected using a CTD rosette sampler. The sample was immediately filtered first through a 3 m and then through a 0.2 m polycarbonate membrane filter. A nucleic acid extraction was performed on the 0.2  3 m fraction using a DNA/RNA Zymo Mini Prep Plus kit. The DNA was then subject to an ultra low library preparation procotol and sequenced using a PacBio Sequel Iie, generating HiFi reads.

A surface water sample was collected from Lake Salubria, New York, USA in April 2020 during a harmful cyanobacterial bloom that turned the lake a crimson color. Enrichment cultures originating from the water sample and favoring cyanobacteria were grown in lab conditions before metagenomic sequencing. The objective was to identify the causative species of the crimson bloom and to identify its potential to produce cyanotoxins.

An enrichment medium containing a variety of electron acceptors (EA medium), was used to develop an anaerobic enrichment from a Vietnamese rice paddy soil. The EA medium consisted of 6 mM NaNO3, 6 mM Na2SO4, 5 mM ferric citrate, 0.01% yeast extract, 35 mM cellobiose, and 1/4 strength TSB (tryptic soy broth). This BioSample corresponds to the EA enrichment amended with 25 micromolar arsenite before inoculation and sampled 46h after inoculation.

This BioSample corresponds to the EA enrichment grown without arsenic and sampled 46h after inoculation.

Anoxic sediment from Lake Matano, Indonesia was stored under anoxic conditions for approximately 4 years, then mixed with anoxic freshwater media in a 1 to 5 ratio in an anoxic chamber and dispensed in stoppered serum bottles. They were incubated for 319 days at 30 degrees C, with multiple transfers, each time diluting the original sediment with freshwater media.

Biofilm samples were harvested in August, 2010 from the hulls of the USS Bainbridge (Ship#2) at Norfolk Naval Station in Norfolk, VA, USA. The ship hull was sampled after a seven month deployment (January  July, 2010) that started and concluded in Norfolk, VA. Biofilms with a Fouling Rating 20 (i.e. advanced slime - Naval Ships Technical Manual Chapter 081, 2006) were scraped from the air-water interface (starboard, mid-ship) and immediately snap frozen in sterile 50 mL conical tubes using an EtOH-dry ice bath (Supplementary Figure S1). Surface water samples were also collected at a distance of 0.5 to 5.0 m from the hulls of the same vessels and all planktonic material was harvested on 0.22 *m UltraClean Water DNA Filters (MO BIO Laboratories, Inc. Carlsbad, CA, USA) and snap frozen.

biomass in wastewater treatment process

Biopurification system (BPS) are used to treat pesticide wastewater streams on farmyards. The matrix consists of a mixture of agricultural soil and straw and by the pesticide application these environments are highly enriched in pesticides. BPS matrix samples originating from the BPS in Kortrijk were described before (Dealtry, Holmsgaard, et al., 2014), aiming to study the seasonal changes in the pool of MGE content as well as the pesticide compounds that were loaded on the BPS matrix. Samples were collected before start-up in March and during the spraying season in July and September of the agricultural season of 2011. An additional sampling taken just after the seasonal shut down of the BPS in December 2011, is included in this study. Here by a novel metagenomic tool, the accessory genes of the IS1071 composite transposons was targeted by means of a long range PCR method. Aiming to further study the ecological significance of these IS1071 elements in pesticide contaminated environments. Dealtry S, Holmsgaard PN, Dunon V, et al. (2014) Shifts in abundance and diversity of mobile genetic elements to diverse pesticides introduced into an on-farm biopurification system over a year.Keywords: GSC:MIxS;MIMS:6.0

Biopurification system are used as purification system of pesticide wastewater streams. Here we present a pristine artificial BPS composed of commercial flower soil coconut chips and straw. No history of pesticide treatment has been recorded and regarded as a pristine environment unadapted to pesticide pollution. Here by a novel metagenomic tool, the accessory genes of the IS1071 composite transposons was targeted by means of a long range PCR method. Aiming to further study the ecological significance of these IS1071 elements in pesticide contaminated environments.Keywords: GSC:MIxS;MIMS:6.0

Crossbred steers were fed with ragi straw at maintenance levels for three weeks. The rumen digesta was collected and used for further evaluation of the unculturable bacteria and the metabolic processes in the animal. This study also provides an idea on the various glycosyl hydrolases operative in the rumen to bring about the digestion of ingested low quality roughages.

DNA from  human tooth found in the Yakimova Mogila Tumulus, which dates to the Iron Age (450400 BC), near Krushare, Bulgaria. An aristocratic inhumation burial containing rich grave goods was excavated in 2008. A molar from one individual, probably male, was used for DNA analysis.Keywords: GSC:MIxS;MIMS:6.0

DNA from human found in a flat cemetery dating to the Late Bronze Age (15001100 BC) near the village of Vratitsa, Bulgaria. Nine inhumation burials were excavated between 2003 and 2004. A molar from a juvenile male (age 1617) was used for DNA analysis.Keywords: GSC:MIxS;MIMS:6.0

DNA from human tooth found in a Thracian tumulus (burial mound) near the village of Stambolovo, Bulgaria. Two small tumuli dating to the Early Iron Age (850700 BC) were excavated in 2008. For viral metagenomic analysis, 40 specimens were collected from 10 laboratory rabbits which were bred in the Animal Center of Jiangsu university (including 10 feces, 10 oral, 10 blood, 10 skin specimens) in October 2018. Before use, swab was put into 1.5 mL centrifuge tubes 500 uL PBS and vortexed for 5 min at room temperature. The supernatants were then collected after centrifugation (5 min, 14,000g). 40 sample supernatants were pooled into 8 pools with 5 sample each according to sample types, where each type of sample included 2 pools. Supernatants were filtered through a 0.45mm filter (Millipore) to remove eukaryotic and bacterial cell sized particles, and 200 uL of supernatant from each pool was then subjected to a mixture of nuclease enzymes to reduce the concentration of free (nonviral encapsidated) nucleic acids. Remaining total nucleic acid was then isolated using QIAamp MinElute Virus Spin Kit according to manufacturer's protocol. Eight libraries were then constructed using Nextera XT DNA Sample Preparation Kit (Illumina) and sequenced using the MiSeq Illumina platform with 250 bases paired ends with dual barcoding for each pool.

For viral metagenomic analysis, 665 fecal specimens were collected from 72 species of mammals which from several zoos in Hangzhou, Zhejiang Province in 2019. Before use, swab was put into 1.5 mL centrifuge tubes 500 uL PBS and vortexed for 5 min at room temperature. The supernatants were then collected after centrifugation (5 min, 14,000g). 665 sample supernatants were pooled into 69 pools. Supernatants were filtered through a 0.45um filter (Millipore) to remove eukaryotic and bacterial cell sized particles, and 200 uL of supernatant from each pool was then subjected to a mixture of nuclease enzymes to reduce the concentration of free (nonviral encapsidated) nucleic acids. Remaining total nucleic acid was then isolated using QIAamp MinElute Virus Spin Kit according to manufacturer's protocol. Eight libraries were then constructed using Nextera XT DNA Sample Preparation Kit (Illumina) and sequenced using the MiSeq Illumina platform with 250 bases paired ends with dual barcoding for each pool.

High molecular weight DNA extracted from the post-incubated switchgrass adherent rumen microbiome was used as a template for three different sequencing libraries. Two whole genome shotgun sequencing libraries with insert size 200 bp and 300 bp were independently generated from DNA, followed by high-throughput sequencing from both ends, one by 2x125bp using Illumina GAIIx and one by 2x100bp using Illumina HiSeq2000 instruments. Two additional libraries were built with insert sizes of 3kb and 5kb respectively to facilitate genome assembly. Both of these two jumping libraries were sequenced using Illumina GAIIx by 2x75bp pair-end sequencing.

Each group is divided into 3 sampling gradients according to the age of the cattle. Difference analysis. When sampling, select fresh specimens, and use clean bamboo sticks to select stools containing mucus, pus and blood and other suspected pathological components; and stools with no abnormal appearance. In the sugar mills, is generated in large quantities a by-product of the process called filter cake. Especially rich in phosphorus and water, this by-product is used as a natural fertilizer in the soil and in compost. However, the composting needs is human and high operational material and therefore not all plants can have the resources to perform such a process. This procedure aims to stir from time to time the material in the composting process in order to reduce the system temperature and control the proliferation of anaerobic microorganisms. An alternative is to filter cake batteries and leave it to time, which provides the development of a thermophilic microbial community and anaerobic the first weeks. This anaerobic microbial community, are responsible for consuming the nutrients that could be available to the plants when the resultant compound was used as fertilizer in soil. In this study, we address the analysis of microbial communities derived from immature compost filter cake aged 60 days.

Lake Baikal represents the deepest (1637 m) and largest fresh liquid water volume (23,000 km3) in Earth (20% of the unfrozen freshwater). This study describes the microbial communities of the Lake using high throughput sequencing. 30 L of water were filtered through the net (size 27 microns) and through nitrocellulose filters with a pore size of 0.22 microns. Metagenomic sample isolated from hardened residue found in tin box of vaccination kit from the collection of the Mutter Museum of the College of Physicians of Philadelphia. Hardened residue may be dried human lymph. Vaccination kit from Mutter catalogue # 17831.42.16 a kit containing two thumb lancets "with tortoiseshell guards, both with 'Charriere' stamped on the blade; guards are much worm, not identical; on one are four evenly-spaced horizontal shallow cuts, on the other are three similar cuts". Vaccination kit belonged to Dr. Jacob Mendez DaCosta (1833-1900), a pioneering Philadelphia physicians who practiced in Philadelphia from 1853-1891.

Metagenomics allows us to acquire the potential resources from both cultured and uncultured microorganisms in the environment. ANAMMOX, uncultured bacteria, played a crucial role in the removal of ammonia nitrogen in wastewater, which contains considerable organic compounds (e.g., humic substances) that may potentially impact on activity and community dynamics of ANAMMOX bacteria. Thus, the knowledge gained in this study highlights an important role of structural and metabolic potential of ANAMMOX systems under humic substances conditions.

Protocols: C57BL/6J mice were obtained from the Jackson Laboratory (Bar Harbor, Maine, USA). All mice were male and 4-6 weeks old. Thirty-two male C57BL/6J mice, were first randomly divided into 4 groups (WT group, and T2D group). Mice in the T2D group were given an intraperitoneal injection of sterile citrate buffer containing streptozotocin (25 mg/kg, Sigma Aldrich, St. Louis, MO, USA), while mice in the WT group were injected intraperitoneally with the same volume of citrate buffer. After continuous administration of streptozotocin for 5 days, the T2D group was fed a high-fat diet (42% Cal from fat, TD.88137, ENVIGO) for 4 weeks to establish a model of type 2 diabetes. The WT group was given adjusted control diet (4% Cal from fat, TD. 08405, ENVIGO). Fecal samples were collected in different time point to understand the effect of several sequential treatment in gut microbiota. Fecal samples collection was performed at 1, 4, 6 and 10th weeks after 1st injection of streptozotocin. Samples were collected in a sterile Eppendorf tube inside a biosafety cabinet with sterile forceps. Each group consisting eight animals were randomized (group wise) to nullify cage-effect in microbiome studies among the groups. After 10 weeks, all animals were sacrificed according to protocols approved by University of Miami Animal Care Committee. Thirty-two male C57BL/6J mice, were first randomly divided into 4 groups (WT group, and T2D group). Mice in the T2D group were given an intraperitoneal injection of sterile citrate buffer containing streptozotocin (25 mg/kg, Sigma Aldrich, St. Louis, MO, USA), while mice in the WT group were injected intraperitoneally with the same volume of citrate buffer. After continuous administration of streptozotocin for 5 days, the T2D group was fed a high-fat diet (42% Cal from fat, TD.88137, ENVIGO) for 4 weeks to establish a model of type 2 diabetes. The WT group was given adjusted control diet (4% Cal from fat, TD. 08405, ENVIGO). In tumor groups, After 2 weeks of tumor implantation when subcutaneous pancreatic cancer model was established, the two groups of mice were each further randomly divided into two subgroups (WT and WT + GP; T2D and T2D + GP). The WT + GP and T2D + GP groups received intraperitoneal injections of 100 mg/kg of gemcitabine and 10 mg/kg of paclitaxel twice in a week for consecutive 4 weeks, while the WT and T2D groups were only receive equal volume of saline. DNA from the mouse fecal samples was isolated using the Power Soil DNA Isolation Kit (Qiagen) according to manufacturers instructions. All samples were quantified using the Qubit Quant-iT dsDNA High-Sensitivity Kit (Invitrogen, Life Technologies, Grand Island, NY) to ensure that they met minimum concentration and mass of DNA, and were submitted to University of Minnesota Genomics Center for further analysis by Whole Genome Shotgun sequencing (WGS). Shotgun metagenomic library was constructed with the Nextera DNA sample preparation kit (Illumina, San Diego, CA), as per manufacturers specification. Barcoding indices were inserted using Nextera indexing kit (illumina). Products were purified using Agencourt AMpure XP kit (Beckman Coulter, Brea, CA) and pooled for sequencing. Samples were sequenced using MiSeq reagent kit V2 (Illumina).Raw sequences were sorted using assigned barcodes and cleaned up before analysis (barcodes removed and sequences above a quality score, Q&gt;30 taken forward for analyses).

Protocols: Fresh feces of volunteers were collected, frozen and stored in -80 for a few months. The total DNA from every fecal sample was extracted by Magnetic Soil And Stool DNA Kit of TIANGEN BIOTECH (BEIJING) CO., LTD, then constructed into a library and sequenced by Illumina PE150. This process was completed by the Wuhan metware Biotechnology Co., Ltd.There are mainly two methods in QC for DNA samples:(1) DNA degradation degree and potential contamination was monitored on 1%agarose gels. (2) DNA concentration was measured using Qubit dsDNA Assay Kit inQubit 2.0 Flurometer (Life Technologies, CA, USA). OD value is between 1.8~2.0,DNA contents above 1ug are used to constructlibrary. A total amount of 1g DNA per sample was used as input material for the DNA sample preparations. Sequencing libraries were generated using NEBNext Ultra DNA Library Prep Kit for Illumina (NEB,USA) following manufacturers recommendations and index codes were added to attribute sequences to each sample. Briefly, the DNA sample was fragmented by sonication to a size of 350bp,then DNA fragments were end-polished, A-tailed, and ligated with the full-length adaptor for Illumina sequencing with further PCR amplification. At last, PCR products were purified (AMPure XP system) and libraries were analysed for size distribution by Agilent2100 Bioanalyzer and quantified using real-timePCR.

Protocols: Spontaneous pancreatic animal model KRASG12D TP53R172HPdx-Cre (KPC) animals from both genders were enrolled in the study at 1 month of age. PDX-cre (Cre) animals that were age matched with the KPC animals were used as control. Fecal samples were collected at 2 months; 3 months and 4 months of age. Initially, 8-9 animals were kept in each group. At 4 months, all animals were sacrificed according to protocols approved by University of Miami Animal Care Committee. DNA from the mouse fecal samples was isolated using the Power Soil DNA Isolation Kit (Qiagen) according to manufacturers instructions. All samples were quantified using the Qubit Quant-iT dsDNA High-Sensitivity Kit (Invitrogen, Life Technologies, Grand Island, NY) to ensure that they met minimum concentration and mass of DNA, and were submitted to University of Minnesota Genomics Center for further analysis by Whole Genome Shotgun sequencing (WGS). Shotgun metagenomic library was constructed with the Nextera DNA sample preparation kit (Illumina, San Diego, CA), as per manufacturers specification. Barcoding indices were inserted using Nextera indexing kit (illumina). Products were purified using Agencourt AMpure XP kit (Beckman Coulter, Brea, CA) and pooled for sequencing. Samples were sequenced using MiSeq reagent kit V2 (Illumina). Raw sequences were sorted using assigned barcodes and cleaned up before analysis (barcodes removed and sequences above a quality score, Q30 taken forward for analyses).

Protocols: We enrolled 12 Indian Rhesus Macaques (RM), consisting of 8 old animals (age &gt; 18 years) and 4 young animals (age 3-6 years). Animals were housed and blood/tissue/stool samples were collected at the New Iberia Research Center (NIRC) at the University of Louisiana at Lafayette. Fresh fecal samples were collected from anesthetized animals by insertion of a fecal loop into the rectum and swiping several times and stored at -80C. No treatments were done. The only variable is age. DNA from the macaque fecal samples was isolated using the Power Soil DNA Isolation Kit (Qiagen) according to manufacturers instructions. All samples were quantified using the Qubit Quant-iT dsDNA High-Sensitivity Kit (Invitrogen, Life Technologies, Grand Island, NY) to ensure that they met minimum concentration and mass of DNA, and were submitted to University of Minnesota Genomics Center for further analysis by Whole Genome Shotgun sequencing (WGS). Shotgun metagenomic library was constructed with the Nextera DNA sample preparation kit (Illumina, San Diego, CA), as per manufacturers specification. Barcoding indices were inserted using Nextera indexing kit (illumina). Products were purified using Agencourt AMpure XP kit (Beckman Coulter, Brea, CA) and pooled for sequencing. Samples were sequenced using MiSeq reagent kit V2 (Illumina).Raw sequences were sorted using assigned barcodes and cleaned up before analysis (barcodes removed and sequences above a quality score, Q&gt;30 taken forward for analyses).

Samples from two different depths (10 and 20m) were collected on December 13th of 2018 at a mariculture cage of adult gilthead seabream cultures (Sparus aurata) from the Western Mediterranean Sea, close to the coast of Guardamar del Segura (Alicante, Spain). Fish farm cages covered had a hight of 15m. The shallowest sample was collected from inside the net cage, whereas the remaining sample was collected from below this structure. For each depth, one seawater sample (200 L each) was collected and quickly filtered. Seawater samples were then sequentially filtered on board through 20, 5 and 0.22 m pore size polycarbonate filters (Millipore). DNA extraction was performed from the 0.22 and 5 m filters (free-living and particle-attached bacteria, respectively) following the phenol:chloroform protocol extraction. Metagenomes were sequenced using Illumina Nextseq (150 bp, paired-end reads).Keywords: GSC:MIxS;MIMS:6.0

Surface soils (0-20 cm deep, 5 cm diameter cores) were collected from 16 randomly selected locations immediately adjacent to the Tall Wheatgrass Irrigation Field Trial experiment in Prosser, WA. Samples were transported to the Pacific Northwest National Laboratory (PNNL) on ice and stored at 4 until processing. Soils were homogenized on ethanol-sterilized 4 mm sieves, and rocks were removed. Sixty grams (dry weight soil equivalent) were weighed into autoclaved 4 oz jars, and the soils were brought to 75% water holding capacity by addition of sterile deionized water. Three replicate incubations were set up for each of the two sampling time points (n=6). First, the soils were preincubated for one week during which time they were gradually exposed to increasing temperature until the target incubation temperature of 30C average summer temperature  was reached. The incubation temperatures were: 10 C on day 1, 15C on day 3, 25C on day 5 and 30C on day 7. During the pre-incubation water was added to the soils daily to maintain them at 75% water holding capacity by mass. Once at 30C, three incubation jars continued to incubate at 30C, without any further moisture additions. Moisture loss was monitored by mass, until complete desiccation was achieved after 14 days. Three replicate samples were harvested, representing the post-desiccation soils. Sample was stored at -80C until being processed for DNA and RNA extractions.Keywords: GSC:MIxS;MIMS:6.0

Tannins are secondary compounds present in several plants of forage interest. Little is known about the ruminal adaptation mechanisms of native goats from semiarid regions to the tannins presence in the diet, even less when there is variation in the genetic group, and how it will affect productive factors such as feed digestibility. With that in mind, we aim with this study to identify the modulating effect of tannins on adaptive factors of lactating goats with different genetic groups, through the assessment of digestibility and intake of nutrient, ingestive behavior and rumen microbial abundance

The biofilm samples were harvested in August, 2010 from the hulls of the USS Laboon (Ship# 1) at Norfolk Naval Station in Norfolk, VA, USA. The ship hull was sampled after a seven month deployment (January  July, 2010) that started and concluded in Norfolk, VA. Biofilms with a Fouling Rating 20 (i.e. advanced slime - Naval Ships Technical Manual Chapter 081, 2006) were scraped from the air-water interface (starboard, mid-ship) and immediately snap frozen in sterile 50 mL conical tubes using an EtOH-dry ice bath (Supplementary Figure S1). Surface water samples were also collected at a distance of 0.5 to 5.0 m from the hulls of the same vessels and all planktonic material was harvested on 0.22 *m UltraClean Water DNA Filters (MO BIO Laboratories, Inc. Carlsbad, CA, USA) and snap frozen.

The diversity of RNA viruses in Earths oceans remains largely unexplored. Analysis of the RNA metavirome from ~10 liters of seawater from Yangshan harbor near Shanghai identified over 4,500 distinct RNA viruses, nearly doubling the RNA virus diversity previously characterized from all sources. Phylogenomic analysis of these sequences supports the previously establishes five-branch gross structure of the RNA virus evolutionary tree but also resulted in the discovery of several major clades, roughly, at the taxonomic ranks of class, order and family. The largest and most remarkable of these new groups is the 719 member-strong Yangshan virus assemblage that consists of viruses with a simple genome structure, typically encoding only RNA-dependent RNA polymerase (RdRP), capping enzyme, and capsid protein, and is the sister group of the expansive Alphavirus supergroup. A distinct feature of the Yangshan virus assemblage is domain permutation in the RdRP that independently occurred in several clades within this group. Another previously unknown clade appears to share ancestry with the potyviruses, the largest known family of plant viruses. In addition, the Aquatic picorna-like viruses/Marnaviridae clade was greatly expanded, with over 800 new viruses identified. The metavirome contains several RdRP-linked protein domains that have not been previously detected in any RNA viruses, such as the SUMO ubiquitin-like protein, phospholipase A2 and PrsW family protease. Multiple viruses utilize alternative genetic codes implying protist (especially ciliate) hosts. The results of this work indicate that the global RNA virome is vast and enormously diverse. However, phylogenetic analysis of the RdRPs shows that the majority of the discovered viruses fall into previously identified major branches suggesting that the megataxa of RNA viruses are already known.

The purpose of this study was to evaluate if systematic differences occur when different commercially available DNA extraction kits are used for whole metagenomic sequencing (WMS) analysis of the human microbiome. Oral, vaginal, and rectal swabs were collected in replicates of four by a healthcare provider from five participants and randomized to one of four DNA extraction kits. Two extraction blanks and three replicate mock community samples were also extracted using each extraction kit. WMS was completed with NovaSeq 6000 for all samples.Keywords: GSC:MIxS;MIMS:6.0

The sequence data in this project are from metagenomic sequencing of surface water samples collected from Kissena Lake in Queens, New York City on September 26, 2019 during a cyanobacterial bloom dominated by Raphidiopsis (Cylindrospermopsis) raciborskii. The primary objective was to capture the genomic sequence of a North American strain of Raphidiopsis raciborskii from a bloom in a natural lake. The dominant bloom-forming species in this lake at the time of sample collection was microscopically/morphologically identified as Raphidiopsis raciborskii. A secondary objective was to metagenomically profile the co-occurring cyanobacterial community.

The soil microcosm (SM) experiment has been described before (Bers et al. 2013) and aimed at assessing the role of Variovorax in linuron mineralization in agricultural soil. Here by a novel metagenomic tool, the accessory genes of the IS1071 composite transposons was targeted by means of a long range PCR method. Aiming to further study the ecological significance of these mobile genetic elements in pesticide contaminated environments. Briefly, the SM consisted of small glass columns filled with soil originating from a field with a history of linuron treatment. Irrigation was performed discontinuously with sterile tapwater contaning linuron (60 mg/L) with an average irrigation of 0.5 mL per day. The SM was incubated at 25 degrees and after 78 days, irrigation was ceased for 31 days but was resumed on day 110. DNA samples were taken at day 491 of the incubation and the long range PCR performed to asses the IS1071 accessory load.Keywords: GSC:MIxS;MIMS:6.0

The South African borehole of interest is at a depth of 1.34 km (BE326-BH2). This sub-horizontal borehole penetrates 57 meters into a medium to coarse-grained sub-lithic arenite to intersect a NNW striking fault zone where it encountered high-pressure water with a flow rate of 750 L min-1. Since it was first drilled in 2007, it has been sealed off with a high pressure steel valve. The brackish, alkaline paleometeoric water and microbial communities collected from this borehole were first characterized in 2011. PIs Rachel L. Harris, Maggie C. Y. Lau, and Tullis C. Onstott.

The study aims to describe the microbial community of a freshwater reservoir using high throughput sequencing. The reservoir is called Tous and is located in the region of Valencia, Spain. Water was collected and filtered through a series of polycarbonate filters, a 20 micron prefilter, 5 micron (for large cells and eukaryotes) and 0.22 (for planktonic microbes). DNA was extracted from the 0.22 micron filter (small, planktonic fraction) filter to obtain genomic DNA of the microbial community.Keywords: GSC:MIxS;MIMS:6.0

The study aims to describe the microbiota of a freshwater reservoir using high throughput sequencing. The reservoir is called Amadorio and is located in the region of Alicante, Spain. Water was collected and filtered through a series of polycarbonate filters. DNA was extracted from the 0.1 micron and 5 micron filters to obtain genomic DNA for two different size fractions of the microbial community. DNA was sequenced using Illumina HiSeq 2000. This sample represents the metagenome of the 0.1 micron fraction.Keywords: GSC:MIxS;MIMS:6.0

The temporal dynamics of desert soil microbial communities has rarely been investigated. Here, we sampled soils in the central Namib Desert on sixteen different occasions over one year period. Using Illumina-based amplicon sequencing of the 16S rRNA gene, we found that alpha-diversity (richness) was most variable at a given sampling date (spatial variability) than over the course of one year (temporal variability). Community composition remained unchanged across the first 10 months, indicating that spatial sampling might be more important than temporal sampling when assessing beta-diversity patterns in the Namib. Nevertheless, a major shift in microbial community composition was found following a precipitation event. This shift in composition increased CO2 respiration and productivity, corroborating that desert soil microbial communities can resuscitate quickly from dormancy. A better understanding of microbial community stability and its implications for ecosystem functioning are crucial under a global change scenario.

This sample consists of the pooled DNA from triplicate moving-bed biofilm reactors treating waste-water spiked with 10 g/L mecoprop. The three pooled samples were each studied separately with SSU rRNA amplicon sequencing with the BioSample identifiers SAMN06276325, SAMN06276326 and SAMN06276327

Virome of an agricultural soil sample (fertilized with manure) collected in 2016 at the experimental field soil ZOFE in Zurich, Switzerland. Soil viruses were resuspended based on a literature-defined approach, extracted using a 0.22 micron PES filter, concentrated with polyethylene glycol precipitation and purified using caesium chloride ultracentrifugation. Viral DNA was extracted using phenol-chloroform DNA extraction and paired-end sequenced with Illumina HiSeq 2500 Rapid Run mode (2 x 300 bp).Keywords: GSC:MIxS;MIMS:6.0
